uction Boas explores the influence of The Hieroglyphics and the causes behind the rebirth of interest in symbolism in the sixteenth century. The illustrations to this edition were drawn by Albrecht Dürer on the verso pages of his copy of a Latin translation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEmblemsvEarly works to 1800. 0aHieroglyphicsvEarly works to 1800. 0aSymbolismvEarly works to 1800. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh  aAbsence of ants.  aAphrodite.  aBirth, deformed.  aBoundaries.  aCircle.  aCopulation.  aDeath.  aDiscrimination.  aDistribution of justice.  aEgypt.  aEternity.  aFilial affection.  aForeknowledge.  aGluttony.  aGratitude.  aHeavens.  aHephaistus.  aHoroscopist.  aImpurity.  aInfinity.  aJudge.  aLawlessness.  aLoins.  aMagistrate.  aMeasurement.  aNight.  aPederasty.  aPlunderer.  aRecklessness.  aSluggishness.  aSublime.  aTemperance.  aTwilight.  aUnanimity.  aUnstable man.  aVictory.  aWasp.  aWidow.1 aBoas, George.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691215068zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691215068423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691215068.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK